  "prompt": "What are the best books about the late-80s/90s internet industry leading up to the dot-com bubble?",
  "response": "The history of the late-80s/90s internet industry leading up to the dot-com bubble is a fascinating and pivotal period in the evolution of technology and business. There are several books that provide insightful perspectives on this era:\n\n1. **\"Dot.Con: The Greatest Story Ever Sold\" by John Cassidy** - This book dives into the frenzy and eventual collapse of the dot-com bubble, exploring the irrational exuberance and financial mania of the time.\n\n2. **\"The Innovators: How a Group of Hackers, Geniuses, and Geeks Created the Digital Revolution\" by Walter Isaacson** - While it covers a broader range of technological advancements, this book includes significant insights into the development of the internet and the pivotal figures who influenced its growth leading up to the late-90s.\n\n3. **\"Burn Rate: How I Survived the Gold Rush Years on the Internet\" by Michael Wolff** - Michael Wolff offers a firsthand account of his experiences within the internet business during the boom years, providing a detailed narrative of the highs and lows of the industry.\n\n4. **\"Where Wizards Stay Up Late: The Origins of the Internet\" by Katie Hafner and Matthew Lyon** - Though it starts in the earlier era, this book is essential for understanding the foundational technologies and key players that paved the way for the internet industry seen in the late-80s and 90s.\n\n5. **\"The New New Thing: A Silicon Valley Story\" by Michael Lewis** - This book follows the rise of the internet through the story of Netscape and its co-founder Jim Clark, shedding light on the culture of innovation and risk-taking in Silicon Valley during the dot-com boom.\n\n6. **\"High Stakes, No Prisoners: A Winner's Tale of Greed and Glory in the Internet Wars\" by Charles Ferguson** - Ferguson provides an insider's look into the creation and rise of his company, Vermeer Technologies (makers of FrontPage), and the broader context of the 90s internet industry.\n\n7. **\"The Dot-Com Bubble Burst\" by Stephen P. Magee** - This book is an analysis of the economic factors and business practices that led to the rise and fall of many dot-com companies, offering a critical view of the bubble and its aftermath.\n\nThese books offer a mix of historical context, personal anecdotes, and analytical perspectives that collectively provide a comprehensive understanding of the internet industry's rapid growth and subsequent crash in the late 80s and 90s.",
